claim.claim-text:
1. An apparatus to accurately hold an optical fiber within a commercial fiber optic connector comprising: 
a first high precision slice having multiple holes of a first area and a first alignment opening; 
a second high precision slice having multiple holes of a second area and a second alignment opening; 
the holes of the first high precision slice being arranged relative to the first alignment opening so that, when the second high precision slice and the first high precision slice are juxtaposed with one another and the first alignment opening and the second alignment opening are aligned, the holes of the first high precision slice and the holes of the second high precision slice will be offset relative to each other and define an opening having an area less than a smaller of the first area and second area and capable of closely constraining an optical fiber inserted therethrough.

14. A fiber holder of a size suitable for use in a commercial fiber optic connector comprising: 
a first piece having a thickness, a periphery defining a first surface and a second surface opposite the first surface, 
the first piece further having an array of fiber receiving holes of a first substantially circular cross sectional area and extending through the thickness; 
a second piece having a thickness and a periphery defining a first surface and a second surface opposite the first surface, 
the second piece further having an array of fiber receiving holes of a second substantially circular cross sectional area and extending through the thickness; 
The first piece and the second piece being coupled together such that, when the first piece and the second piece are coupled to a low precision piece having a ferrule shaped peripheral surface, centers of the fiber receiving holes in the first piece are offset from centers of the fiber receiving holes in the second piece by an amount sufficient to closely constrain optical fibers inserted therethrough.

23. A method of making an optical fiber holder usable in a commercial connector, the method comprising: 
making holes of a first size in a first plate, the first size being larger than a cross sectional area of an optical fiber; 
making holes of a second size in a second plate, the second size being larger than the cross sectional area of the optical fiber; 
misaligning the holes in the first plate relative to the holes in the second plate such that the holes in the first plate partially overlap the holes in the second plate by an amount that will create openings of at least the cross sectional area and having a sufficient shape to accept optical fibers inserted through the holes and also closely constrain the optical fibers inserted therein.
